[Note that the comment period ends 14 Sep 2015.

In 2012 (http://www.idsociety.org/uploadedFiles/IDSA/Policy_and_Advocacy/Current_Topics_and_Issues/Emerging_Infections_and_Biothreats/Letters/To_Agencies/IDSA%20Comments%20on%20H5N1%20Select%20Agent%20Proposal%20121412.pdf), Robbin Weyant, PhD, Director, Division of Select Agents and Toxins, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, recommended that influenza viruses containing the hemagglutinin from the Goose/Guangdong/1/96 Lineage be classified as a select agent.

Several criteria were considered, including 1) the ability of the strain to be transmitted from person to person, 2) the characteristics of the strain in question, compared to naturally circulating strains, and 3) the availability of medical countermeasures (i.e., drugs, vaccines and diagnostics) to mitigate the risk of disease. Circulating HPAI H5N1 influenza viruses containing the hemagglutinin (HA) from the Goose/Guangdong/1/96 lineage do not currently pose a severe threat to public health and safety because they are not readily transmitted between humans. However, H5N1 strains with increased mammalian transmissibility do pose a severe threat to public health and safety, and it is crucial that extensive biosafety and biosecurity measures be taken to prevent accidental release or an act of bioterrorism. ...

IDSA [Infectious Diseases Society of America] recommends that HPAI H5N1 influenza viruses containing the HA from the Goose/Guangdong/1/96 lineage viruses be regulated as select agents by HHS. H5N1 viruses are currently regulated as select agents by the US Department of Agriculture (USDA) with a focus on agricultural animal health. The involvement of HHS in H5N1 select agent regulation will ensure that the impact on human health is considered when agents are being reviewed. ... [more at URL above]

To understand the classification of organisms as select agents by the USDA and CDC, see http://www.selectagents.gov/SelectAgentsandToxinsExclusions.html. - Mod.LK]
